Disk Forensics > [T3]: Extracting Network interfaces and configurations

(1) Network interfaces and configurations

The first step would be identifying physical network cards connected to the system. This information can be found under SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\NetworkCards.There you will find a subkey for each network card, as displayed.

 

Network cards - (zoom in)

  1. 'NetworkCards' registry key.
  2. 'NetworkCards' registry key path.
  3. List of network cards. Each card is assigned a unique number (11 and 2 in the above example). Clicking on each number will show the adapter name and GUID.
  4. GUID stands for 'Globally Unique Identifier.'  The registry is a central repository that contains information about objects. The registry uses GUID to reference/identify any object. Objects could be network interfaces, applications, devices..etc. Each physical network adapter, ethernet or wireless, will have its unique GUID, which we will use in the next step to extract network configurations.
  5. "Description" contains a description of the network card, usually the adapter's name.
Once we have identified physical NICs, we should identify available interfaces. Wait for a second, is not a network 'card' and 'interface' the same thing? No! A network card is a physical adapter. An interface, on the other hand, could be physical or virtual. In other words, each physical 'card' must have an interface, but not all interfaces are associated with physical cards. Multiple tools, such as Wireshark and VMware, may install virtual interfaces to operate.

 

List of virtual interfaces available to Wireshark - (zoom-in)

 

A list of available Interfaces and their corresponding configurations can be found under \SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Services\Tcpip\Parameters\Interfaces. There you will see subkeys named after the GUIDs of the physical network cards you got in the first step, in addition to any virtual interface.

 

Interfaces configurations - (zoom in)

  1. 'Interfaces' registry key.
  2. 'Interfaces' registry key path.
  3. List of GUIDs (network cards).One GUID for each interface. Clicking on each GUID will show the network configurations for that interface.
  4. The 'EnableDHCP' value indicates whether the system was assigned an IP via DHCP or manually (static). '1' means a DHCP-assigned IP, and '0' means a static IP.
  5. 'DhcpIPAddress' contains the IP issued by the DHCP server If DHCP was enabled.
  6. 'LeaseObtainedTime' shows when this DHCP IP address was assigned to the system and when it will renew.
  7. 'DhcpNetworkHint' is a unique identifier for each wireless network SSID. It's used to streamline connecting to a previously accessed wireless network. This value is presented in HEX format and can be converted to ASCII using CyberChef.

 

CyberChef - (zoom in)

  1. Encoded network name.
  2. Decoded network name.

One thing to note, in the first screenshot, 'Network cards,' we can see only two physical network cards. However, in the second screenshot, 'Interfaces configurations,' we see four different interfaces for the same machine. Two belong to the physical network cards, and the other two are virtual interfaces.
